Serialization, a brief note.

Java has a built-in serialization mechanism that turns an object graph into a stream of bytes, which you can write to a file or send over a socket, and then reconstruct the objects on the other side. It is opt-in: a class participates only if it implements the serializable marker interface, which has no methods; it just flags the class as eligible. Fields you do not want written, like a password, you mark transient, and they are skipped. You write objects through an object-output-stream and read them back through an object-input-stream.

Now, I am showing you this as a warning, not as a recommendation. Java's built-in serialization is convenient, but it has serious, well-known problems. It has been a recurring source of security vulnerabilities, because deserializing data from an untrusted source can be tricked into executing arbitrary code. It tightly couples your class's internal structure to the on-disk wire format, so changing the class can break old data. And the java development kit team is actively working to replace the whole mechanism.

So for real persistence, reach for a structured format instead: jason, through libraries like Jackson or Gson, or yaml, or protocol buffers, or avro. We will use Jackson heavily once we get to Spring. Treat the serializable interface as legacy knowledge: you need to recognise it when you meet it in old code, but you should rarely add it to anything new.
